{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% set meta = card_data.meta %}
{% set protocol = card_data.protocol %}
{% set contrasts = card_data.contrasts %}
{% set headline = card_data.headline %}
{% set odds = card_data.single_manager_odds %}
{% set naive_pct = (protocol.forking_paths_naive_rate * 100) | round | int %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/s6.css?v={{ asset_version }}">
{% endblock %}

{% macro dir_cell(d) %}{% if d == "+" %}+{% elif d == "-" %}&minus;{% else %}&mdash;{% endif %}{% endmacro %}

{% macro contrast_label(id) %}{% if id == "h_size" %}Disciplined sizing versus equal weighting{% else %}Fast decay versus slow decay{% endif %}{% endmacro %}

{% macro verdict_label(verdict) %}{% if verdict == "ship" %}usable signal{% elif verdict == "weak_tell" %}weak signal{% else %}indistinguishable{% endif %}{% endmacro %}

{% macro verdict_row(c, row) %}
<div class="s6-row s6-row--{{ row.verdict }}">
  <div class="s6-row__head">
    <span class="s6-row__name">{{ row.signature | replace("_", " ") }}</span>
    <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="{{ row.verdict }}">{{ verdict_label(row.verdict) }}</span>
  </div>
  <div class="interval-stat" data-domain="auc"
       data-domain-min="0" data-domain-max="1"
       data-point="{{ row.auc_point }}" data-lo="{{ row.auc_lo }}" data-hi="{{ row.auc_hi }}"
       data-floor="{{ c.significance_floor }}" data-bar="{{ c.usability_bar }}">
    <span class="interval-stat__label">worst deciding-cell directional AUC</span>
    <span class="interval-stat__value">{{ "%.3f"|format(row.auc_point) }}</span>
    <div class="interval-stat__rail s6-rail">
      <div class="interval-stat__band"></div>
      <div class="s6-rail__mark s6-rail__null" title="null AUC 0.5"></div>
      <div class="s6-rail__mark s6-rail__floor" title="familywise significance floor"></div>
      <div class="s6-rail__mark s6-rail__bar" title="usability bar 0.65"></div>
      <div class="interval-stat__point"></div>
    </div>
    <span class="interval-stat__range">
      95% band {{ "%.3f"|format(row.auc_lo) }}&ndash;{{ "%.3f"|format(row.auc_hi) }}
      &middot; significance floor {{ "%.3f"|format(c.significance_floor) }}
      &middot; usability bar {{ "%.2f"|format(c.usability_bar) }}
    </span>
  </div>
  <p class="s6-row__stats">
    adj p = {{ "%.3f"|format(row.worst_adj_p) }} across {{ row.n_deciding_cells }} deciding cells
    &middot; secondary T={{ meta.secondary_t }} AUC {{ "%.3f"|format(row.secondary_t_auc) }}
    (labeled secondary, never deciding).
  </p>
  {% if not row.declared %}
  <p class="s6-row__note">No declared direction for this contrast &mdash; computed and reported, but
    <strong>cannot become a usable signal</strong>; a surprising result would require a fresh study.</p>
  {% endif %}
  {% if row.reversed %}
  <p class="s6-row__note s6-row__note--reversed">Direction <strong>reversed vs the declaration</strong>:
    familywise-significant with the sign opposite to the pre-declared mechanism &mdash; an anomaly to
    document for a possible v2, not a discovery with the sign quietly flipped.</p>
  {% endif %}
</div>
{% endmacro %}

{% block demo_content %}
<section class="s6-refusal" aria-labelledby="s6-refusal-title">
  <p class="s6-refusal__eyebrow">Decision</p>
  <h2 id="s6-refusal-title">Monthly returns do not support an operational sizing or decay classification</h2>
  <p>The test found <strong>0 usable signals / 1 weak signal / 11 indistinguishable results</strong>.
    The weak signal pointed in the opposite direction to the mechanism stated before the test.
    For an individual manager, the honest answer is to ask for exposures, positions, or trades.</p>
</section>

<section class="s6-question-pair" aria-label="Two hidden processes tested from monthly returns">
  <article>
    <span class="s6-question-pair__tag">Sizing</span>
    <h2>Disciplined sizing versus equal weighting</h2>
    <p>Could conviction weighting leave a stable signature in volatility, tails, or drawdowns after
      dozens of positions have been compressed into one monthly return?</p>
  </article>
  <article>
    <span class="s6-question-pair__tag">Decay</span>
    <h2>Fast decay versus slow decay</h2>
    <p>Could a three-month alpha half-life be distinguished from a 36-month half-life using only the
      slope and dependence structure of monthly returns?</p>
  </article>
</section>

<section class="s6-focal" aria-labelledby="s6-focal-title">
  <div class="s6-focal__heading">
    <div>
      <p class="s6-refusal__eyebrow">Closest result</p>
      <h2 id="s6-focal-title">One weak signal, still below usability</h2>
    </div>
    <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="weak_tell">weak signal</span>
  </div>
  {{ verdict_row(contrasts[0], contrasts[0].rows[4]) }}
  <p class="s6-focal__takeaway">The interval is statistically distinguishable from blind ranking,
    but it lies on the wrong side of the declared mechanism. It cannot be turned into a classifier
    by reversing the story after seeing the result.</p>
</section>

<aside class="s6-exhibit" aria-label="What this exhibit shows">
  <h2 class="s6-exhibit__title">What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <div class="s6-exhibit__block">
    <h3 class="s6-exhibit__sub">How to read it</h3>
    <p>The grey mark is blind ranking at AUC 0.50. The amber mark is the familywise
      <em>significance</em> boundary; the blue mark is the higher <em>usability</em> bar at
      {{ "%.2f"|format(meta.auc_min) }}. A result must clear both in the declared direction across
      every deciding cell. The weak result does not.</p>
    <p class="s6-exhibit__bridge">The complete method and derivation are in the
      <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/{{ card.id }}.html">technical method</a>.</p>
  </div>
</aside>

<details class="s6-all-results">
  <summary>See the other eleven reviewed intervals</summary>
  <p class="s6-grid__gapnote">An indistinguishable result is an informative result, not missing
    evidence: the signature failed to separate the two known synthetic populations.</p>
  {% for c in contrasts %}
  <div class="s6-contrast">
    <h3 class="s6-contrast__label">{{ contrast_label(c.id) }}</h3>
    <p class="s6-contrast__meta">{{ c.n_deciding_cells }} deciding cells; significance boundary
      {{ "%.3f"|format(c.significance_floor) }}, usability bar {{ "%.2f"|format(c.usability_bar) }}.</p>
    <div class="s6-contrast__rows">
      {% for row in c.rows %}
        {% if not (c.id == "h_size" and row.signature == "drawdown_shape") %}{{ verdict_row(c, row) }}{% endif %}
      {% endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
  {% endfor %}
</details>

<details class="s6-protocol">
  <summary>How the test was fixed in advance</summary>
  <div class="s6-protocol__body">
    <p>The six signatures, expected directions, window lengths, thresholds, and deciding cells were
      fixed before the simulated paths were inspected. Trying six independent 5% tests would produce
      at least one false alarm about <strong>{{ naive_pct }}%</strong> of the time
      (1 &minus; 0.95<sup>6</sup>). The Westfall&ndash;Young maximum-statistic test instead controls
      the chance of any false claim across the closed family. This is familywise control, not a
      false-discovery rate screen over an open pool.</p>

    <table class="s6-family">
      <caption>Six pre-specified returns-only signatures and their expected directions.</caption>
      <thead><tr><th>Signature</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Disciplined sizing</th>
        <th>Fast decay</th><th>Known confound</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {% for f in protocol.family %}
        <tr><td>{{ f.signature | replace("_", " ") }}</td><td>{{ f.mechanism }}</td>
          <td class="s6-family__dir">{{ dir_cell(f.direction_h_size) }}</td>
          <td class="s6-family__dir">{{ dir_cell(f.direction_h_decay) }}</td>
          <td>{{ f.confound }}</td></tr>
        {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <dl class="s6-constants">
      <dt>Usability bar</dt><dd>AUC &gt; {{ "%.2f"|format(meta.auc_min) }}</dd>
      <dt>Familywise &alpha;</dt><dd>{{ "%.2f"|format(meta.familywise_alpha) }} (Westfall&ndash;Young maximum statistic)</dd>
      <dt>Current study</dt><dd>{{ meta.n_per_class }} per class &middot; {{ meta.n_perm }} permutations</dd>
      <dt>Confirmatory study</dt><dd>{{ meta.confirmatory.n_per_class }} per class &middot; {{ meta.confirmatory.n_perm }} permutations</dd>
      <dt>Rolling windows</dt><dd>{{ meta.rolling_windows[0] }} and {{ meta.rolling_windows[1] }} months</dd>
      <dt>Deciding horizon</dt><dd>{{ meta.decision_t }} months ({{ meta.secondary_t }} months is secondary)</dd>
    </dl>
    <p>The confirmatory study uses a fresh seed and a wider stress grid. Its outcome is
      <strong>unknown by design</strong>. Any change after looking at these results requires a fresh
      study; the current results remain on record.</p>
  </div>
</details>

<section class="s6-panel s6-close">
  <h2 class="s6-panel__title">What the result permits</h2>
  <p class="s6-headline">No reviewed returns-only signature supports classifying a manager&rsquo;s
    sizing discipline or alpha decay.</p>

  <div class="power-gate">
    <span class="power-gate__title">What even a usable signal would &mdash; and would not &mdash; mean</span>
    <p class="power-gate__reason">
      An AUC of {{ "%.2f"|format(odds.auc) }} {{ odds.pair_odds }}. Applied to a
      <strong>single</strong> manager it is {{ odds.single_manager }} &mdash; which is why any
      usable signal would be a <strong>conversation prompt</strong>, never a standalone score.
      An indistinguishable result is <strong>an informative result, not missing evidence</strong>: if the
      fingerprint does not survive in a clean world where the trait is the only difference, it will
      not survive a dirtier one.
    </p>
  </div>

  <ol class="s6-ladder">
    {% for rung in card_data.ladder %}
    <li class="s6-ladder__rung"><span class="s6-ladder__num">{{ rung.rung }}</span>{{ rung.label }}</li>
    {% endfor %}
  </ol>
  <p class="s6-close__note">No manager-facing use precedes external validation against positions or
    exposures where the process is directly observable.</p>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>The test statistic is the Mann&ndash;Whitney AUC &mdash; the probability a random positive-class
manager outranks a random negative-class one on the signature. Significance is the Westfall&ndash;Young
max-statistic familywise permutation test: relabel the pooled managers thousands of times, take the
maximum |AUC &minus; 0.5| over the whole six-signature family each time, and adjust each observed
deviation against that null of the max. The +1s make the p-value valid at finite permutation count;
the max statistic absorbs the correlation among signatures (they share one return path), so it is
exact familywise control over a small pre-committed family &mdash; not an FDR screen.</p>
<p>Each verdict worst-cases the direction-oriented AUC and the adjusted p over every deciding cell
(an intersection&ndash;union test over the ic &times; smoothing-&theta; grid), so a ship must hold its
bar on the overlay-stressed cells too. The interval band is the Hanley&ndash;McNeil SE at the observed
AUC. All numbers on this page come from the precomputed analysis &mdash; the browser only
positions them on the page.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/s6-signatures.js"></script>
{% endblock %}
